        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#1f77b4">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Highest margins</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Anil Basu</strong>'s victory at Arambagh, WB had the largest margin CPM or any party had seen: over 5.9 lakh votes.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?margin=min">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#ff7f0e">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Lowest margins</h3>
            <p><p>On the other hand, <strong>Som Marandi</strong> (BJP) and <strong>Konathala Ramakrishna</strong> (INC) won by just 9 votes in Bihar, 1998 and AP, 1989 respectively.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?votes=max">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#2ca02c">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Most voters</h3>
            <p><p>Until 2004, <strong>Outer Delhi</strong> had the highest number of voters polled (15 lakh). After the 2008 delimitation, that mantle went to <strong>Malkajgiri, AP</strong> (12 lakh)</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?votes=min">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#d62728">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Fewest voters</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Lakshadweep</strong> has the lowest number of votes counted consistently across the years, with close competition from <strong>Dadra &amp; Nagar Haveli</strong>.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?candidates=max">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#9467bd">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Most candidates</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Nalgonda, AP</strong> fielded a record-breaking 480 candidates in the 1996 elections, with <strong>Belgaum, KA</strong> a close second in the same year.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?candidates=1">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#8c564b">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Uncontested wins</h3>
            <p><p>Since 1989, no election was won uncontested. <strong>Srinagar, J&amp;K</strong> was the last, where Mohammad Shafi Bhat of JKN won without competition.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?women=max">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#e377c2">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Most women</h3>
            <p><p>Only two elections had women candidates exclusively: <strong>Karur, TN</strong> (1967) and <strong>Panskura, WB</strong> (1977). Only 8 elections have had more women than men.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?age=max">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#7f7f7f">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Old candidates</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Arif Ahmed Shaikh Jafhar</strong> (NBNP) contested the 2009 elections from Dhhule, MH at age 99, making him the oldest candidate ever in India.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?partywin=min">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#bcbd22">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Struggling parties</h3>
            <p><p>The <strong>Doordarshi Party</strong>, founded by Baba Jai Gurudev in 1980, has the record of contesting 716 seats across 3 years <em>without a single victory</em></p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="summary?partywin=max">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#17becf">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Winning parties</h3>
            <p><p>The <strong>INC</strong> is among the most successful parties, being one of the few parties that has won more than 50% of the seats it has ever contested in</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="pattern?party=CONG">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#1f77b4">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Congress bastions</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Chhindwara, in Madhya Pradesh</strong>, is the only constituency to have voted for the Congress <em>every election</em> for the last 15 elections.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="pattern?party=BJP">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#ff7f0e">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>BJP bastions</h3>
            <p><p>Only 8 constituencies have voted for BJP every time since 1989. 5 are in Madhya Pradesh, 2 in Gujarat, and 1 in Rajasthan.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="pattern?winning=1">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#2ca02c">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Bellweathers</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Faridabad, in Haryana</strong>, is the only constituency that has constistently voted for the national winning party in every election since 1977.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    
      <div class="topic" href="pattern?anti-incumbent=1">
        <div class="thumbnail" style="background-color:#d62728">
          <div class="caption">
            <h3>Anti-incumbents</h3>
            <p><p><strong>Bara Banki, in Uttar Pradesh</strong>, has voted against the incumbent party in every single election since its inception in 1957.</p></p>
          </div>
        </div>
